{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525619"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:16:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:16:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14087"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583915"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:31:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:31:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14087"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14087"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.22,0.06,0.06,0.51]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6755"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111947"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6755"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14087"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94011"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"2823"},{"type":"tags","id":"2889"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14703"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14706"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35131"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111947"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about a rash that has been present for the past three days. She reports having a sore throat two weeks ago that resolved on its own. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The rash consists of pink, non-pruritic, slightly raised lesions with serpiginous borders and central clearing on her trunk and proximal limbs, sparing her face, palms and soles. The lesions appear and disappear within hours. She also complains of joint pain in her knees and ankles and has been using a heat pack for her discomfort.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Erythema ab igne","Erythema multiforme","Urticaria","Tinea corporis","Erythema marginatum"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation in this case is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eerythema marginatum\u003C/strong\u003E, a characteristic rash associated with group A Streptococcus though rare in adults. The rash is described as pink, non-pruritic lesions with serpiginous borders and central clearing, which appear and disappear within hours, often with hot conditions. This transient nature is typical of erythema marginatum. The patient\u0027s history of a recent sore throat (likely (\u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E) and joint pain further support this diagnosis. Patients may also present with carditis and Sydenham chorea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythema multiforme\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with target-like lesions that are fixed and do not come and go rapidly. It is often associated with herpes simplex virus infections or medication reactions, which are not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrticaria\u003C/strong\u003E (hives) can present with transient, raised, and sometimes ring-shaped lesions. However, urticaria is typically intensely pruritic, unlike the rash described in this patient. Additionally, urticaria is not associated with a recent streptococcal infection or joint pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETinea corporis\u003C/strong\u003E (ringworm) can present with ring-shaped lesions, but these are typically scaly, pruritic, and do not appear and disappear rapidly. Tinea corporis is a fungal infection and would not be associated with joint pain or a recent sore throat.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythema ab igne\u003C/strong\u003E is a reticulated, hyperpigmented rash that occurs due to chronic exposure to heat. It typically appears on areas of the body that have been repeatedly exposed to heat sources, such as heating pads or laptop computers. The rash in erythema ab igne is fixed and does not appear and disappear rapidly, unlike the transient nature of the rash described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythema marginatum is one of the major criteria in the Jones criteria for diagnosing acute rheumatic fever. Its presence, along with the history of a recent streptococcal infection (sore throat) and joint pain (which could represent polyarthritis, another major criterion), strongly suggests acute rheumatic fever. Further evaluation, including anti-streptolysin O titers and echocardiography, would be warranted to confirm the diagnosis and assess for cardiac involvement. Treatment is with penicillin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Erythema marginatum is a characteristic rash associated with acute rheumatic fever.","Erythema marginatum presents as transient, ring-shaped lesions with central clearing.","The presence of erythema marginatum, along with other major manifestations, supports the diagnosis of acute rheumatic fever using the Jones criteria."],"references":["Vijayan V, Sukumaran S. Erythema marginatum. The Journal of Pediatrics. 2023: 258.  Available at: https://www.jpeds.com/article/S0022-3476(23)00040-9/fulltext","Hartley M, Gomez J. Rheumatic fever. In Dermnet NZ [online]. 2016 Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/rheumatic-fever"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94011"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14087"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20978"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20978"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/EPObAkXaprE6gou8qs1pvokcQAexwO.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/EPObAkXaprE6gou8qs1pvokcQAexwO.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94011"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-22T12:00:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-22T12:00:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6755"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111947"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://